# Shopify ⇄ eBay order fulfillment

This skill takes shipping data exported from eBay (an Order ID plus its tracking
number) and marks the corresponding order as **fulfilled in Shopify**, attaching the
tracking number so the customer gets a shipping-confirmation email. The seller buys
labels on eBay; this skill just syncs the resulting tracking back into Shopify, which
eBay's native sync sometimes misses.

The whole job is a matching problem: every Shopify order that originated on eBay
carries the **eBay Order ID** (e.g. `17-14751-34838`), and Shopify's order search
finds an order by that ID. So the reliable key is the eBay Order ID — never the buyer
name or item title, which can collide or be formatted inconsistently.

## Inputs you'll receive

The user supplies eBay Order ID → tracking number pairs in one of three forms. Extract
the pairs first, then proceed identically regardless of source:

- **CSV** — eBay's "Paid and shipped" / "Sold" report. The columns that matter are
  `Order Number` (the eBay Order ID), `Tracking Number`, and `Shipping Service`. Item
  title and buyer are useful only for the human-readable summary.
- **Screenshots** — the eBay Seller Hub *Orders → Shipping labels* page. Read the
  `Order #` column and the tracking number under `Track package`.
- **Typed pairs** — the user just lists IDs and tracking numbers.

### CSV parsing notes

The eBay report has quirks worth handling deliberately so you don't drop or
double-count orders:

- The first line is blank/comma-filler and the real header is on line 2. There's also
  a trailing summary line like `4 record(s) downloaded` and a `Seller ID:` line at the
  bottom — ignore both.
- A **multi-item order spans several rows** sharing the same `Order Number`. The first
  row carries the buyer/address; the item rows carry each item and the tracking number.
  Collapse these into **one** order with one tracking number — fulfilling the order
  ships all its line items together.
- A row can have an empty `Tracking Number` (label not yet created). Skip it and flag
  it; don't try to fulfill without tracking.

## Carrier detection — read the tracking number, not the label

Determine the carrier from the **tracking number format**, and let it override
whatever the eBay "Shipping Service" column claims. eBay's service label is what the
buyer selected and is frequently wrong when the seller actually shipped via a different
carrier.

- Tracking starts with **`1Z`** → **UPS**
- Tracking starts with **`9`** (e.g. `9400…`, `9405…`, `9261…`) → **USPS**

If a tracking number matches neither pattern, don't guess — fulfill without a forced
carrier (Shopify will still record the number) and flag it in the summary so the user
can set the carrier manually. Shopify auto-generates the correct tracking URL once the
company is set to a recognized carrier.

